[SourceTitle "01 Introduction to the Scandinavian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-scandinavian/course/79, variation/32153"]

1. e4 d5 {Welcome to the reliable waters of the Scandinavian Defense - affectionately 
referred to by many as the 'Scandi'! One of the greatest advantages of 1.e4 d5 is 
that it is far easier to learn compared to pillars of opening theory like the 
Sicilian Defense and 1.e4 e5. In creating this repertoire I drew on my 15+ years of 
experience with the Scandinavian to present the lines that a 1.e4 d5 player is likely 
to encounter with the goal of getting you 'up and running' with this opening as soon 
as possible. Though I will present a full Scandinavian repertoire, the primary 
subject of our work is the following line:} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 *

[Event "IM John Bartholomew's Scandinavian"]
[Site "Main Line - 5.Nf3 Bg4"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Main Line - 5.Nf3 Bg4 #1"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 Main Line - 5.Nf3 Bg4"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-scandinavian/course/79, variation/32154"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 {White develops a piece with tempo. What could be more 
natural?} Qd8 {The queen has done her job in recovering the pawn, so now retreats to 
safety. Alternatives like 3...Qd6 and 3...Qa5 are also playable} ({in fact, I used to 
exclusively play 3...Qa5}) {, but those lines are more complex as Black queen tends 
to come under attack in various ways. In my experience you will face 2.exd5 Qxd5 
3.Nc3 about 90% of in the Scandinavian and can therefore look forward to having this 
position after 3...Qd8 on the board quite often against 1.e4!} 4. d4 {Occupying the 
center.} Nf6 5. Nf3 {This is White's most frequently played fifth move, and it is 
consistent with the well-worn chess maxim of 'knights before bishops.'} Bg4 {In the 
3...Qa5 Scandinavian Black often prefers to develop the light-square bishop to f5. 
Why, then, does Black prefer g4 here? The answer lies in the pressure on d4. With 
Black's queen on d8, his light-square bishop creates indirect pressure on d4 and 
limits the number of attacking setups White can adopt. Moreover, the pin limits 
White's attacking aspirations with Bf1-c4 and Nf3-e5.} 6. Bc4 {threatens the typical 
tactical motif 7.Bxf7+ followed by 8. Ne5+. As a Scandinavian player, you NEED to be 
aware of this idea! Black should address White's threat with} e6 {and after} 7. h3 
Bxf3 8. Qxf3 {White's queen threatens b7.} c6 {Black enjoys a solid position. For 
instance,} 9. O-O $6 Qxd4 $1 *

