position after 3...Qd8 on the board quite often against 1.e4!} 4. d4 {Occupying the 
center.} Nf6 5. Nf3 {This is White's most frequently played fifth move, and it is 
consistent with the well-worn chess maxim of'knights before bishops.'} Bg4 {In the 
3...Qa5 Scandinavian Black often prefers to develop the light-square bishop to f5. 
Why, then, does Black prefer g4 here? The answer lies in the pressure on d4. With 
Black's queen on d8, his light-square bishop creates indirect pressure on d4 and 
limits the number of attacking setups White can adopt. Moreover, the pin limits 
White's attacking aspirations with Bf1-c4 and Nf3-e5.} 6. Bc4 {threatens the typical 
tactical motif 7.Bxf7+ followed by 8. Ne5+. As a Scandinavian player, you NEED to be 
aware of this idea! Black should address White's threat with} e6 {and after} 7. h3 
Bxf3 8. Qxf3 c6 {Black enjoys a solid position. For instance,} 9. Ne2 Nbd7 10. O-O 
Bd6 11. b3 O-O 12. Bb2 {We are following Bok,B (2488)-Glek,I (2408) Belgium 2012. 
Here I like} a5 $5 *

