forcing a trade of queens.} 12. Qxd5 cxd5 {My choice when I faced the immensely 
talented GM Jeffery Xiong in the summer of 2015.} 13. c4 dxc4 14. Bxc4 $1 {The most 
challenging. White recovers the pawn, and Black must be wary of attempts to open the 
position with d4-d5 or f2-f4-f5.} Nd7 15. Bb3 Bd6 16. f4 Nb6 {This is a valid 
alternative to 16...0-0.} *

