3.Nc3 about 90% of in the Scandinavian and can therefore look forward to having this 
position after 3...Qd8 on the board quite often against 1.e4!} 4. d4 {Occupying the 
center.} Nf6 5. Nf3 {This is White's most frequently played fifth move, and it is 
consistent with the well-worn chess maxim of'knights before bishops.'} Bg4 {In the 
3...Qa5 Scandinavian Black often prefers to develop the light-square bishop to f5. 
Why, then, does Black prefer g4 here? The answer lies in the pressure on d4. With 
Black's queen on d8, his light-square bishop creates indirect pressure on d4 and 
limits the number of attacking setups White can adopt. Moreover, the pin limits 
White's attacking aspirations with Bf1-c4 and Nf3-e5.} 6. h3 {Also most common.} Bxf3 
$1 {When prompted, Black should not hesitate to make this exchange.} 7. Qxf3 c6 8. 
Be3 {Protecting d4.} e6 {With pawns now established on e6 and c6 Black has 
established the characteristic'light-square restriction' structure, which is also 
present in related openings like the Slav Defense and Caro-Kann Defense. The effect 
of this pawn arrangement is three-fold: 1) d4-d5 is discouraged, 2) White's 
light-square bishop is restricted, and 3) Black obtains a convenient anchor for a 
knight on d5. As a Scandinavian player I predict you will come to love the solidity 
this structure offers.} 9. Bd3 Nbd7 {Sometimes it's helpful to think about which 
moves are 'mandatory' in a position. For Black, ...Nb8-d7 will inevitably be played, 
as the knight has no business on the a6 square. Therefore Black should play this move 
immediately and keep the dark-square bishop back for a moment; this bishop could 
conceivably to go to e7, d6, or b4 (as in the lines with queenside castling from 
White).} 10. O-O-O {This should again be met by} Bb4 $1 11. Ne4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Nf6 13. 
Bg5 Be7 $1 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Kb1 {Bida,M (2212)-Baratosi,D (2424) Baile Olanesti 
2013} a5 $5 {Black may continue with...a5-a4 and even...Ra8-a5. Stockfish claims a 
small edge for White, but I think it's more smitten by White's typical space 
advantage than anything else. It's tough for White to create huge problems with the 
opposite color bishops in this semi-closed position.} *

