knight on d5. As a Scandinavian player I predict you will come to love the solidity 
this structure offers.} 9. Bd3 Nbd7 {Sometimes it's helpful to think about which 
moves are 'mandatory' in a position. For Black, ...Nb8-d7 will inevitably be played, 
as the knight has no business on the a6 square. Therefore Black should play this move 
immediately and keep the dark-square bishop back for a moment; this bishop could 
conceivably to go to e7, d6, or b4 (as in the lines with queenside castling from 
White).} 10. O-O-O {This should again be met by} Bb4 $1 11. Ne2 $5 {A good try for an 
edge. White avoids minor piece exchanges.} Nd5 12. Qg3 g6 13. Bh6 {Heberla,B 
(2545)-Djukic,N (2537) Plovdiv 2013. Here I suggest} b5 $5 {staking out queenside 
space and securing the knight on d5 by controlling c4. Black may soon play...Bb4-f8 
to offer a trade of dark-square bishops.} *

