1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 c6 8. Bf4 {A 
relatively new try that was recommended by GM John Shaw in his book 'Playing 1. e4 - 
Caro-Kann, e5 & Minor Lines.' White posts the dark-square bishop actively and dares 
Black to capture on d4. Snatching the pawn with} Qxd4 {is not recommended because 
White obtains a dangerous initiative:} 9. Nb5 $1 cxb5 10. Bxb5+ Nbd7 11. Qxb7 {You 
don't want anything to do with this position as Black!} *

[Event "IM John Bartholomew's Scandinavian"]
[Site "Main Line - 5.Nf3 Bg4"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Main Line - 5.Nf3 Bg4 #19"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 Main Line - 5.Nf3 Bg4"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-scandinavian/course/79, variation/338244"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 c6 8. Bf4 {A 
relatively new try that was recommended by GM John Shaw in his book 'Playing 1. e4 - 
Caro-Kann, e5 & Minor Lines.' White posts the dark-square bishop actively and dares 
Black to capture on d4.} e6 9. O-O-O {White claims that he has an improved version of 
the line 8. Be3 e6 9.O-O-O. In addition to the more active dark-square bishop, an 
important basis for White's claim is that his queen assists in the defense of White's 
knight on c3.} Bb4 {Black should still go ahead and play this irritating move. Up 
until now I've been painting a rosy picture of White's chances in this line, but the 
bishop on f4 has a drawback: Bxc3 11. Qxc3 Nd5 is in the air.} 10. Ne2 {I faced this 
move in a game against GM S.P. Sethuraman in the 2017 PRO Chess League (an online 
league with a 15+2 time control) .} Qd5 $1 {Attacking f3 and a2 and forcing a 
favorable queen trade. This is a common occurence when White castles queenside, as we 
explored in the 8. Be3 e6 9.O-O-O Bb4 lines.} 11. Qxd5 cxd5 {Black could also 
consider capturing with the knight, but re-taking toward the center makes the most 
sense. The half-open c-file may be a source of counterplay for Black.} 12. c3 Be7 13. 
Ng3 Nc6 14. Bd3 O-O {Black had a comfortable game in Sethuraman - Bartholomew, PRO 
Chess League 2017. I continued with ...Rfc8, with an eye toward expending on the 
queenside (...a7-a6, ...b7-b5, possibly with ... Nc6-a5-c4 in mind) . I also 
challenged White's dark-square bishop with ... Nf6-e8 and ...Be7-d6.} *

