1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 c6 8. Bf4 {A 
relatively new try that was recommended by GM John Shaw in his book 'Playing 1. e4 - 
Caro-Kann, e5 & Minor Lines.' White posts the dark-square bishop actively and dares 
Black to capture on d4.} e6 9. O-O-O {White claims that he has an improved version of 
the line 8. Be3 e6 9.O-O-O. In addition to the more active dark-square bishop, an 
important basis for White's claim is that his queen assists in the defense of White's 
knight on c3.} Bb4 {Black should still go ahead and play this irritating move. Up 
until now I've been painting a rosy picture of White's chances in this line, but the 
bishop on f4 has a drawback: Bxc3 11. Qxc3 Nd5 is in the air.} 10. Kb1 $5 {As usual, 
this king nudge is useful. It doesn't stop Black from executing his idea, however.} 
Bxc3 11. Qxc3 Nd5 12. Qg3 Nxf4 13. Qxf4 Nd7 {Petrov - Heinzel, Novi Sad 2016. White 
has additional space plus a bishop versus a knight, but Black's prospects look 
reasonable to me. After a move like ...Qd8-f6 he should look to castle queenside} *

