1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bc4 {I've found that strong players 
seem to slightly prefer this move over 5.Nf3. A possible explanation is that White's 
knight may be developed to e2 or White might utilize the f3 square for the queen, and 
a good player will be aware of these possibilities.} a6 $1 {A surprising idea that 
has done much for the credibility of the 3...Qd8 Scandinavian. Black prepares...b7-b5 
and, ideally, ...c7-c5!, temporarily gambiting a pawn. I first became aware of this 
line by reading'The 3...Qd8 Scandinavian: Simple and Strong' by Daniel Lowinger. 
Lowinger's book is an excellent resource for aspiring 3...Qd8 Scandinavian players, 
and I have incorporated some of his findings in to the following analysis.} 6. a4 {is 
a natural reaction to control b5, but the tradeoff is that White weakens b4. Black 
can exploit this with} Nc6 $1 {when the knight is looking to settle on b4.} 7. Nge2 
Bf5 8. O-O Nb4 9. Bb3 e6 10. Ng3 Bg6 11. f4 {I faced this thrust in a blitz game on 
the Internet Chess Club against GM Stefan Kristjansson.} Qd7 $1 {Overprotecting f5 
and enabling long castling.} 12. d5 $6 {Pressing forward is logical, as White is 
hoping to deflect the e6-pawn and achieve f4-f5. Black can dish out some punishment, 
however.} O-O-O 13. dxe6 Qxd1 14. Nxd1 Nxc2 15. Bxc2 Bxc2 16. Ne3 Bd3 {Black wins 
