1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bc4 {I've found that strong players 
seem to slightly prefer this move over 5.Nf3. A possible explanation is that White's 
knight may be developed to e2 or White might utilize the f3 square for the queen, and 
a good player will be aware of these possibilities.} a6 $1 {A surprising idea that 
has done much for the credibility of the 3...Qd8 Scandinavian. Black prepares...b7-b5 
and, ideally, ...c7-c5!, temporarily gambiting a pawn. I first became aware of this 
line by reading'The 3...Qd8 Scandinavian: Simple and Strong' by Daniel Lowinger. 
Lowinger's book is an excellent resource for aspiring 3...Qd8 Scandinavian players, 
and I have incorporated some of his findings in to the following analysis.} 6. Be3 $5 
{Rare but dangerous: White defends d4 and keeps f3 free for his queen, intending long 
castling. GM Sahaj Grover played this way against me at the 2015 UT Dallas Fall FIDE 
Open.} e6 {Amazingly, this was a novelty when I played it.} 7. Qf3 $5 {GM Grover 
responds aggressively. By now you may have noticed that lines involving Qd1-f3 and 
0-0-0 are some of White's most ambitious in the 5.Bc4 line. If I could get a'do-over' 
I would play this!} Nbd7 $5 8. O-O-O Bd6 9. Nge2 Rb8 {intending...b7-b5. The pawn may 
advance all the way to b4 and/or the light-square bishop will make an appearance on 
b7.} *

