1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bc4 {I've found that strong players 
seem to slightly prefer this move over 5.Nf3. A possible explanation is that White's 
knight may be developed to e2 or White might utilize the f3 square for the queen, and 
a good player will be aware of these possibilities.} a6 $1 {A surprising idea that 
has done much for the credibility of the 3...Qd8 Scandinavian. Black prepares...b7-b5 
and, ideally, ...c7-c5!, temporarily gambiting a pawn. I first became aware of this 
line by reading'The 3...Qd8 Scandinavian: Simple and Strong' by Daniel Lowinger. 
Lowinger's book is an excellent resource for aspiring 3...Qd8 Scandinavian players, 
and I have incorporated some of his findings in to the following analysis.} 6. Nf3 b5 
7. Bb3 c5 $1 {Pawn avalanche! Black attacks the White d4-pawn and threatens 8...c4, 
trapping the bishop. Even though this concept has been accepted 3...Qd8 Scandinavian 
practice, I can attest that even strong 1.e4 players have been caught completely 
unaware of its existence. For example, GM Samuel Sevian was not aware of this line 
when I sprung it on him in November 2015.} 8. dxc5 {Accepting the'gift.'} Qxd1+ 9. 
Nxd1 {Out of 52 games to reach this position in my database, White recaptured with 
the knight on 45 occasions.} e6 10. a4 {This should be met by} b4 {keeping the 
queenside closed. Following} 11. a5 $5 {(I give only this line because the idea of 
Bb3-a4 gives the game some independent flavor; on other moves the second player has 
no issues) Black has a three reasonable continuations:} Bxc5 12. Ne5 {Kovacevic,A 
(2535)-Djukic,N (2523) Pancevo 2006. Here it's simplest to whisk the king away with} 
O-O $1 {because, as Lowinger also points out, putting the king on e7 (either before 
or after Bb3-a4+) takes away a convenient retreat for the dark-square bishop in the 
event of Ne5-d3. Continuing a couple play further with} 13. O-O Bb7 {I can't imagine 
White being able to claim any edge.} *

