[SourceTitle "03 Flank Attack - 5.Bc4 a6"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-scandinavian/course/79, variation/342079"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bc4 {I've found that strong players 
seem to slightly prefer this move over 5. Nf3. A possible explanation is that White's 
knight may be developed to e2 or White might utilize the f3 square for the queen, and 
a good player will be aware of these possibilities.} a6 $1 {A surprising idea that 
has done much for the credibility of the Qd8 Scandinavian. Black prepares ...b7-b5 
and, ideally, ...c7-c5!, temporarily gambiting a pawn. I first became aware of this 
line by reading 'The Qd8 Scandinavain: Simple and Strong' by Daniel Lowinger. 
Lowinger's book is an excellent resource for aspiring Qd8 Scandinavian players, and I 
have incorporated some of his findings in to the following analysis.} 6. Bb3 $5 
{Prophylaxis against ...b7-b5.} c5 $1 {Black can execute the main idea anyways!} 7. 
Nf3 $5 {When originally developing this repertoire in late 2015, I saw that this move 
had been played in only game: Sermek,D (2532) -Djukic, N (2521), Portoroz 2005. It 
looked interesting to me, and I ultimately recommended that Black meet it with e6. 
While e6 is playable, it completely escaped my attention that} b5 $1 {simply 
transposes to our main line in the Flank Attack chapter! My only excuse is that weird 
things happen when you analyze the same opening for hours on end:) Since it makes no 
sense to analyze additional variations when the main line is so reliable for Black, I 
changed this variation to reflect the transposition and I recommend you handle the 
rare move order} ({6. Bb3!? c5! 7.Nf3!?}) {in this fashion. Many thanks to the 
Chessable user 'ZukertortsGhost' for spotting this transposition.} *

[Event "IM John Bartholomew's Scandinavian"]
[Site "Early Bishop Sortie - 5.Bg5"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Early Bishop Sortie - 5.Bg5 #1"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "04 Early Bishop Sortie - 5.Bg5"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-scandinavian/course/79, variation/32248"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bg5 {Let me say upfront: you won't face 
this move too often. Although the dark-square bishop development is fine, the vast 
majority of players prefer to develop their kingside instead. Daniel Lowinger devotes 
nearly 30 pages of analysis to 5.Bg5 in'The 3...Qd8 Scandinavian: Simple and Strong', 
but I think knowledge of only a few key lines is sufficient against this rare 
continuation.} h6 $1 {Helpful: this pawn nudge secures a safe square for Black's 
light-square bishop in the future (... Bc8-f5 and ...Bf5-h7 if need be). Compared to 
5.Bc4 a6 6.Bg5 h6?! Black need not lose sleep over Bg5xf6 and a quick Qd1-h5, hitting 
f7.} 6. Bh4 c6 {The natural} 7. Nf3 {has been played exactly once according to my 
database.} Bg4 {Pinning looks like the correct reaction. Black will continue 
with...e6-e7, ...Bf8-e7, ... 0-0, ...Nb8-d7, etc.} *

