[SourceTitle "04 Early Bishop Sortie - 5.Bg5"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-scandinavian/course/79, variation/32243"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bg5 {Let me say upfront: you won't face 
this move too often. Although the dark-square bishop development is fine, the vast 
majority of players prefer to develop their kingside instead. Daniel Lowinger devotes 
nearly 30 pages of analysis to 5.Bg5 in 'The 3...Qd8 Scandinavian: Simple and 
Strong', but I think knowledge of only a few key lines is sufficient against this 
rare continuation.} h6 $1 {Helpful: this pawn nudge secures a safe square for Black's 
light-square bishop in the future (... Bc8-f5 and ...Bf5-h7 if need be). Compared to 
5.Bc4 a6 6.Bg5 h6?! Black need not lose sleep over Bg5xf6 and a quick Qd1-h5, hitting 
f7. If White intends to demonstrate a defect in Black's last move, then} 6. Bxf6 {is 
clearly critical, damaging Black's structure and refusing to lose time. Now} exf6 7. 
Bc4 Bb4 8. Qe2+ Qe7 9. O-O-O {was seen in the Grandmaster encounter Filippov,A 
(2558)-Golod,V (2575) Tashkent 2009. Here I like the look of} Nc6 10. Nd5 Qxe2 11. 
Nxe2 Bd6 12. Rhe1 O-O {Such a middlegame can be compared to the Exchange Ruy Lopez: 
Black has a slightly compromised pawn structure, but in return he posses a pair of 
bishops. As long as Black carefully weighs piece exchanges (you don't want to 
flagrantly trade down with a worse structure) he should be fine.} 13. Nec3 Be6 *

