1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bg5 {Let me say upfront: you won't face 
this move too often. Although the dark-square bishop development is fine, the vast 
majority of players prefer to develop their kingside instead. Daniel Lowinger devotes 
nearly 30 pages of analysis to 5.Bg5 in'The 3...Qd8 Scandinavian: Simple and Strong', 
but I think knowledge of only a few key lines is sufficient against this rare 
continuation.} h6 $1 {Helpful: this pawn nudge secures a safe square for Black's 
light-square bishop in the future (... Bc8-f5 and ...Bf5-h7 if need be). Compared to 
5.Bc4 a6 6.Bg5 h6?! Black need not lose sleep over Bg5xf6 and a quick Qd1-h5, hitting 
f7.} 6. Bh4 c6 7. Bc4 Bf5 8. Bxf6 {GM Arkadij Naiditsch (2700+ at the time) chose 
this delayed capture against GM Nikola Djukic at the 2012 World Chess Olympiad in 
Istanbul, Turkey. It has not been repeated, but given the harmlessness of the 
alternative, 8.Nf3, I'm giving Naiditsch's move as the main line. Lowinger gives 
8.Bxf6 a '?!' mark and deems White's change of heart to be a 'early psychological 
victory' for Black. I don't think it's so bad, but it also shouldn't refute Black's 
setup (of course!).} exf6 9. Qe2+ Be7 10. O-O-O O-O 11. Nf3 Bb4 $1 {Inconvenient 
timing for White! Now Black can wreck White's queenside pawns at a moment's notice.} 
12. g4 $5 Bh7 {Understandably, GM Djukic didn't want to tempt fate, so he makes a 
safe-and-sound retreat.} 13. Bd3 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 $1 Qa5 15. Ne4 $6 {GM Naiditsch was 
playing top board for Germany in this match, and I'm sure he wanted to crush GM 
Djukic and his out-gunned Montenegro team. This aggression is highly speculative, 
however.} Qxa2 16. c3 {Otherwise White gets mated on a1.} Be7 {Better is the 
preparatory} 17. h4 $1 {but after} Nd7 18. g5 h5 $1 {Black can keep the kingside 
closed and therefore stands better with his extra pawn.} *

