1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. g3 {This kingside fianchetto is a fairly popular 
plan against 3...Qa5, but in the 3...Qd8 Scandinavian I've seldom encountered it. 
Still, Black should know how to meet it, as White's plan to exert pressure on the 
center and Black queenside via the h1-a8 diagonal is a sophisticated approach.} Nf6 
5. Bg2 {Now I'll give two possible continuations:} c6 {A solid reply. Black will 
develop the bishop outside the chain with.....Bf5 and build our usual Scandinavian 
setup: ...e6, ...Nbd7, ...Be7/d6/b4, ...0-0, etc.} 6. Nf3 Bf5 7. d4 e6 8. O-O h6 $1 
{Preparing a useful'cubby hole' for the bishop on h7 in the event of Nf3-h4.} 9. Re1 
Be7 {Oftentimes it's a judgment call whether to put the dark-square bishop on e7 or 
d6. In this case I somewhat prefer e7 because Black's queen remains connected to 
d4/d5, and on d6 it would be blunted by the pawns on g2+h2. Oh yes, and 9...Bd6 
10.d5! could be unpleasant!} 10. Ne2 O-O 11. c4 Nbd7 12. Nc3 Re8 13. Bf4 Qb6 14. Qe2 
Rad8 {Black is holding his own despite the disadvantage in space.} *

