1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 4. g3 {This kingside fianchetto is a fairly popular 
plan against 3...Qa5, but in the 3...Qd8 Scandinavian I've seldom encountered it. 
Still, Black should know how to meet it, as White's plan to exert pressure on the 
center and Black queenside via the h1-a8 diagonal is a sophisticated approach.} Nf6 
5. Bg2 {Now I'll give two possible continuations:} c6 {A solid reply. Black will 
develop the bishop outside the chain with.....Bf5 and build our usual Scandinavian 
setup: ...e6, ...Nbd7, ...Be7/d6/b4, ...0-0, etc.} 6. Nf3 Bg4 {I've often developed 
the bishop here, but lately I've been re-thinking the wisdom of this square because 
of the following idea:} 7. O-O e6 8. h3 Bh5 9. d4 Nbd7 10. Re1 Be7 11. Ne2 $1 {Now 
Ne2-f4 is coming and Black must part with the light-square bishop. Contrary to the 
Main Line where Black also parts with the light-square bishop I believe White has 
more flexibility with his pawn structure (the c-pawn is already free) and strong 
bishop on the h1-a8 diagonal.} O-O 12. Nf4 *

