knight on e5 before it gets too comfortable.} 8. Bf4 Nxe5 9. Bxe5 Bd6 10. Qe2 O-O 11. 
O-O-O {Sharp! All of this is hypothetical since Nbd7, but I'm giving such a line 
because it's important to understand how Black should react when White adopts an 
aggressive (albeit rare) setup.} b5 {Two can play at this game! Not only does this 
gain space on the queenside, it also prepares active development of the light-square 
bishop to b7.} 12. Bd3 Bb7 {Chances are balanced in this unexplored position.} *

