1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. d4 e5 {This counter-thrust is considered to be the 
straight-forward equalizer. I also like it because it's in the spirit of 1.e4 d5: 
destroy White's center! By the way, 3...Nc6 is also fully playable if you're looking 
for a more complicated game} ({this could transpose to 3.Nf3 Bg4 4.Be2 Nc6}) {.} 4. 
Nf3 {This is likely White's best try, developing and maintaining the tension. Black 
can respond in two ways:} exd4 {A safer response than the enterprising 4...Nc6!?. 
Black can expect to reach equality after this exchange.} 5. Nxd4 Bb4+ $1 
{Wrongfooting White. White cannot block on d2, and if White responds with 6.c3, then 
Black's queen will be cozy on d5 since Nb1-c3 is no longer possible.} *

