Nf3 {This is likely White's best try, developing and maintaining the tension. Black 
can respond in two ways:} exd4 {A safer response than the enterprising 4...♘c6!?. 
Black can expect to reach equality after this exchange.} 5. Qxd4 Qxd4 6. Nxd4 Bc5 7. 
Be3 Nf6 $5 {Inviting White to force the issue.} 8. Nb5 Bxe3 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 Bc1 
$1 {A neat point. The bishop attacks b2 in original fashion!} 11. Nc3 Bxb2 12. Rd1+ 
Bd7 13. Nb5 Nc6 {In this complex position Black's chances are greater, as White has 
trouble saving the a8-knight. For instance:} 14. Bc4 Ke7 15. Nac7 Na5 16. Bb3 Nxb3 
17. axb3 a6 $1 18. Nd4 Bc3+ 19. Ke2 Rc8 {Black rounds up the knight and enjoys a 
decisive advantage.} *

