1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. d4 e5 {This counter-thrust is considered to be the 
straight-forward equalizer. I also like it because it's in the spirit of 1.e4 d5: 
destroy White's center! By the way, 3...Nc6 is also fully playable if you're looking 
for a more complicated game} ({this could transpose to 3.Nf3 Bg4 4.Be2 Nc6}) {.} 4. 
dxe5 Qxd1+ $1 {This is the point. Black does not leap at the first available 
opportunity to recover the pawn; instead, he simply swaps queens, strands White's 
king in the center, and looks to develop while attacking e5.} 5. Kxd1 Nc6 6. f4 
{Greedy! The following game is illustrative of the play Black generates when White 
tries to hang on to his ill-gotten gain:} Bf5 $1 {It's tempting to develop the bishop 
to g4 with check, but the bishop is well-placed on f5, attacking c2.} 7. c3 $2 O-O-O+ 
8. Ke1 f6 $1 {Commit this idea to memory! Black happily opens lines, trusting in his 
lead in development, White's exposed king, and the numerous weaknesses already 
present in White's camp.} 9. Bb5 fxe5 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. fxe5 Bc5 12. Nf3 Nf6 $1 
{Lovely.} 13. exf6 Rhe8+ 14. Kf1 Bd3# *

