1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 {In my opinion this is an underrated line. White does 
not block his c-pawn as he does with 3.Nc3 and may therefore try for d2-d4, c2-c4, 
and only then Nb1-c3. The lines I cover in this section are the most forcing in the 
entire repertoire, so make sure you review them so you aren't caught trying to 
remember your theory in a sharp position!} Bg4 {Developing and pinning.} 4. Be2 {In 
the past - especially in blitz and bullet but even over-the-board - I have sometimes 
played} Nf6 $6 {followed by... e7-e6, ...Bf8-e7, and...0-0. However, I'm forced to 
conclude that such a development scheme is too passive. Consider a natural 
continuation:} 5. d4 e6 6. h3 Bh5 7. O-O Be7 8. c4 Qd8 9. Qb3 Qc8 10. Nc3 O-O 
{Apparently Black hasn't done anything wrong, but after} 11. g4 Bg6 12. Ne5 $1 {White 
is about to win the bishop pair to complement her already impressive pawn structure 
and space advantage. Degraeve,J (2536)-Kovarcik,G (2165) Saint Affrique 1999 
continued} Nbd7 13. Nxg6 hxg6 14. Bf3 c6 15. Bf4 Rd8 16. Rfe1 Bf8 17. Rac1 a5 18. a3 
Ne8 {(Black already has no constructive plan)} 19. c5 $5 Nef6 20. Na4 Nd5 21. Bxd5 
cxd5 22. Nb6 Qc6 23. Nxa8 Rxa8 24. a4 {and Black resigned.} *

