not block his c-pawn as he does with 3.Nc3 and may therefore try for d2-d4, c2-c4, 
and only then Nb1-c3. The lines I cover in this section are the most forcing in the 
entire repertoire, so make sure you review them so you aren't caught trying to 
remember your theory in a sharp position!} Bg4 {Developing and pinning.} 4. Be2 Nc6 
$1 {The most principled and best move. Even though White's setup looks modest, an 
all-out war for the center is brewing with d2-d4 and c2-c4 on the agenda for White. 
With 4...Nc6 Black fights for the pivotal d4 square and enables queenside castling.} 
5. d4 O-O-O 6. c4 Qf5 7. Be3 Bxf3 {Black initiates a forcing sequence.} 8. Bxf3 $1 
Nxd4 9. Bxd4 Qe6+ 10. Be2 Qe4 11. Nc3 $6 {does not impress:} Qxd4 12. Qc2 Qe5 13. O-O 
e6 14. Bf3 Bd6 15. g3 Nf6 16. Nb5 $1 c6 17. Nxa7+ Kc7 18. b4 {This was Rausis,I 
(2496)-Matamoros Franco,C (2462) Las Palmas 1999. White is trying to muddy the 
waters, but with a stranded knight on a7 Black has a tidy reply:} Qf5 $1 19. Qb3 Ra8 
{and White loses material. One nice line is} 20. b5 ({hoping for 20...Rxa7 21.b6+}) 
Bc5 $1 21. Rab1 b6 $1 22. Nxc6 Ra3 {winning the bishop on f3.} *

