1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nf3 {In my opinion this is an underrated line. White does 
not block his c-pawn as he does with 3.Nc3 and may therefore try for d2-d4, c2-c4, 
and only then Nb1-c3. The lines I cover in this section are the most forcing in the 
entire repertoire, so make sure you review them so you aren't caught trying to 
remember your theory in a sharp position!} Bg4 {Developing and pinning.} 4. Be2 Nc6 
$1 {The most principled and best move. Even though White's setup looks modest, an 
all-out war for the center is brewing with d2-d4 and c2-c4 on the agenda for White. 
With 4...Nc6 Black fights for the pivotal d4 square and enables queenside castling.} 
5. d4 O-O-O 6. c4 Qf5 7. Be3 Bxf3 {Black initiates a forcing sequence.} 8. Bxf3 $1 
Nxd4 9. Bxd4 Qe6+ 10. Be2 Qe4 11. O-O Qxd4 12. Qa4 e6 13. Nc3 Bd6 14. Bf3 $1 {was 
Bruzon Batista,L (2641)-Kurajica,B (2525) La Laguna 2010. GM Gawain Jones awarded 
this move an exclamation point when annotating this game for chesspublishing.com, so 
it must be taken seriously.} Ne7 {A novelty that GM Jones did not analyze back in 
2010. Development remains Black's top priority! Kurajica played 14...Qf4, but despite 
the inconvenience to White's king after 15.Rfd1 Qxh2+ 16.Kf1 it was Black who turned 
out to be the victim of a vicious attack.} 15. Nb5 Qb6 16. Nxa7+ Kb8 17. Nb5 {Gaining 
the a-pawn has cost White time.} Nf5 18. b4 Be7 {Material is equal, and Black has 
weathered White's initiative without breaking a sweat. The engine rates Black's 
chances as slightly better here. Note that 19.c5 will be answered by 19...Qa6, 
forcing a queen trade.} *

