1. e4 d5 {Believe it or not, you will encounter more than a few players who will 
decline the proffered d-pawn! Maybe they're suspicious of Black's kind gesture? :)} 
2. d4 {The Blackmar-Diemer Gambit. Taking the pawn is best, but if you're a French 
Defense or Caro-Kann Defense player you may prefer 2...e6/2...c6, transposing!} dxe4 
3. Nc3 e5 $5 {In the process of writing this repertoire I discovered that this line - 
the so-called'Lemberger Defense' - was held in high regard by the authors over at 
ChessPublishing.com, and it's also recommended by GM Christian Bauer in'Play the 
Scandinavian.' Of course Black can try to hang on to the e4-pawn with 3...Nf6 or 
