[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "im-john-bartholomews-scandinavian/course/79, variation/32363"]

1. e4 d5 {Believe it or not, you will encounter more than a few players who will 
decline the proffered d-pawn! Maybe they're suspicious of Black's kind gesture? :)} 
2. d4 {The Blackmar-Diemer Gambit. Taking the pawn is best, but if you're a French 
Defense or Caro-Kann Defense player you may prefer 2...e6/2...c6, transposing!} dxe4 
3. Nc3 e5 $5 {In the process of writing this repertoire I discovered that this line - 
the so-called'Lemberger Defense' - was held in high regard by the authors over at 
ChessPublishing.com, and it's also recommended by GM Christian Bauer in'Play the 
Scandinavian.' Of course Black can try to hang on to the e4-pawn with 3...Nf6 or 
3...Bf5, but having looked at 3...e5 I think it's an attractive counterattack that 
takes the wind out of the sails of a would-be gambiteer.} 4. Nge2 Nc6 5. d5 Nce7 6. 
Ng3 f5 {This is mentioned by both GM Bauer and ChessPublishing.com} ({though they 
both give 6...Nf6 as their main line}) {, and I think it's best.} 7. Bg5 $5 a6 
{Controlling b5. Black has spent several tempi on pawn moves, but White's development 
lead doesn't make much difference in the absence of concrete threats.} 8. Bc4 h6 9. 
Be3 Nf6 {Not f4? 10.Qh5+ followed by 11.Qxe5.} 10. Nh5 {This is Sawyer,T-Owens,J/corr 
BDG thematic 1997.} Neg8 $1 {Black's defenses hold fast! With d6 now being a 
convenient square for the queen, one possible setup is...Qd8-d6, ...Bc8-d7, 
and...0-0-0. Black stands clearly better with the extra pawn.} *

